# YAML templates for chart-review-author

Full field-by-field templates for the guideline package artifacts produced
by the `chart-review-author` skill.

## `meta.yaml`

```yaml
# <task_id> — chart-review guideline (draft)
task_id: <task_id>
task_type: phenotype_validation     # or cohort_classification
review_unit: patient                # or encounter / episode
# Lifecycle: draft → calibrated → locked.
# The skill loader reads this field to gate LOCK-only actions.
# Set to "draft" when authoring; promote flips it to "locked".
status: draft
manual_version: 0.1.0-draft
index_anchor: index_date
output_shape: outcome-first         # outcome-first | evidence-first | hybrid | timeline | narrative
overview_prose: |
  <2-3 paragraph synthesis of what the chart review answers and what the
  final labels mean. Written for a clinical reviewer who hasn't seen the
  source references.>
denominator: "<who is in scope>"
index_event: "<the anchor event, e.g. 'lung cancer diagnosis encounter'>"
source_document_priority:
  - pathology_report
  - imaging_report
  - clinical_note
  - problem_list
time_windows:
  - id: <name_kebab>
    label: "<human description, e.g. '24 months prior to index encounter'>"
final_output: <criterion_id_for_main_outcome>
```

## `criteria/<field_id>.yaml`

One file per criterion. Use the simplest `answer_schema` that captures the
answer faithfully.

```yaml
id: <field_id>
prompt: "<one sentence question>"
answer_schema:
  enum: [yes, no, no_info]   # or:
  # type: boolean
  # type: [number, "null"]
cardinality: one
time_window: <id_from_meta.time_windows>   # optional
group: <group_label>                       # e.g. pathology, imaging, codes, clinical
is_applicable_when: <DSL expression>       # optional gate
derivation: <DSL expression>               # optional, for derived fields
extraction_guidance: |
  <2-4 sentences on where to look: note types, OMOP tables, code families.
  If codes are unknown: # TODO: confirm codes>
guidance_prose:
  definition: <1-3 sentences defining the concept precisely>
  # PREFERRED — split prose into the four axes below. Each is a string
  # (typically a bullet list); reviewers and downstream tooling
  # (chart-review-improve, calibration) consume them as separate axes.
  satisfying_examples: |
    - "<positive example verbatim sentence from a chart>" → yes
    - "<another positive example>" → yes
  non_satisfying_examples: |
    - "<negative example verbatim sentence from a chart>" → no
    - "<another negative example>" → no
  boundary_examples: |
    - "<ambiguous case verbatim>" → <disambiguation rule>
  failure_modes: |
    - <common authoring or reviewer mistake to watch for>
  # LEGACY — single examples blob. Still parses for backward compatibility,
  # but new criteria should use the four-axis split above. Don't mix the
  # two forms in the same criterion; pick one.
  # examples: |
  #   - "<positive example>" → yes
  #   - "<negative example>" → no
```

The four-axis split is the lift-B convention (see
`skills/chart-review/references/atomic-criteria.md`). Failure modes are
first-class authoring information — they prevent the most common
abstraction errors and give `chart-review-improve` clean targets when
proposing edits.

## `keyword_sets/<id>.yaml`

Seed only when the references name specific synonyms or abbreviations.

```yaml
id: <id>
description: <one sentence on what concept these terms signal>
terms:
  - <phrase>
  - <phrase>
source: <citation or "reviewer-supplied">
```

## `code_sets/<id>.yaml`

Seed only when you can confidently name the exact codes from the references.

```yaml
id: <id>
description: <one sentence on what these codes capture>
codes:
  - code: <ICD/LOINC/SNOMED code>
    description: <short label>
excludes:
  - code: <code>
    reason: <why excluded, e.g. "history-only, not active disease">
source: <citation>
```

## `edge_cases.yaml`

Seed only when references explicitly warn about a trap or exception.

```yaml
edge_cases:
  - id: <edge_case_id>
    pattern: |
      <Description of the clinical scenario that is the trap.>
    applies_to: [<criterion_ids>]
    failure_mode: <what an agent typically does wrong here>
    correct_answer_hint: <what the correct answer/action is>
    source: <citation if from a reference>
```
